## Example 4 — Interpret $f(5) = 12$ in Context

A function $f(t)$ represents the distance (in miles) a car has traveled after $t$ hours. Interpret $f(5) = 12$.

### Step 1: Identify the Input and Output

- Input: $t = 5$ (hours)
- Output: $f(5) = 12$ (miles)

### Step 2: Write in Words

"After 5 hours, the car has traveled 12 miles."

### Step 3: Compute Average Speed

$$\text{Average speed} = \frac{\text{distance}}{\text{time}} = \frac{12}{5} = 2.4 \text{ mph}$$

### Step 4: Consider Context

The average speed of 2.4 mph suggests the car may have been stuck in traffic, walking speed, or the trip included many stops. Context matters when interpreting function values.

✅ Answer: After 5 hours, the car has traveled 12 miles (average speed of 2.4 mph).

